      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="https://www.facebook.com/LeslieforColorado/"><img src="https://scontent.fapa1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-1/cp0/p50x50/46110182_2103163249735231_8400532839258390528_n.jpg?_nc_cat=110&_nc_sid=dbb9e7&_nc_ohc=pcI0YVaINTYAX__IAaw&_nc_ht=scontent.fapa1-1.fna&_nc_tp=27&oh=8b4f40cc02eeabc19e76fb9c167a11d6&oe=5FA8B611" alt="" /></a><a href="https://www.facebook.com/LeslieforColorado/">Representative Leslie Herod<a href="https://www.facebook.com/LeslieforColorado/"></a></a><a href="https://www.facebook.com/LeslieforColorado/posts/3574828062568735"></a><a href="https://www.facebook.com"><i></i></a><p>“Some medications are available to reduce the symptoms of sickle cell disease, but the only cure that’s approved in the United States is a bone marrow transplant, and there’s a roughly 5% of dying from treatment complications, said Dr. Chris McKinney, a pediatric hematology oncologist at Children’s.</p><p> Children’s and other hospitals are participating in a study testing a gene therapy treatment approved in Europe, but otherwise there have been few new options for patients since the first drug to reduce symptoms was approved in the 1990s, he said.”</p><p> <a href="https://www.facebook.com/denverpost/">The Denver Post</a></p><a href="https://www.google.com/amp/s/www.denverpost.com/2020/10/12/childrens-hospital-colorado-sickle-cell-disease/amp/">Some medications are available to reduce the symptoms of sickle cell disease, but the only cure that’s approved in the United States is a bone marrow transplant, and there’s a roughly 5…<img src="https://external.fapa1-2.fna.fbcdn.net/safe_image.php?d=AQDx6ajZsebIJkq-&w=540&h=282&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.denverpost.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F10%2FTDP-L-sicklecell100720-cha-487.jpg%3Fw%3D1024%26h%3D683&cfs=1&upscale=1&fallback=news_d_placeholder_publisher&_nc_cb=1&_nc_hash=AQAFF8p_pZqxAtn5" alt="" width="500" height="262" caption="" /></a><p>denverpost.com</p><p>Children’s Hospital Colorado raising